{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"996cf367-f7cc-4a08-bcb1-abf2f61bb888","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01VCVPXUeZfH5ijogJqTiGR5","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Configuring crash dump collection"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01SPMNUka7fDeP6tQKs87FGu","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"ls -la /tmp/sv-97f3378640964325adef5d41f5abc14f/ 2>/dev/null","description":"Check for existing files","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check for existing files"}],"interactionId":"522d73b8-57a8-4403-8b76-c6be5bfc9606","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to configure automatic crash dump collection for a NativeAOT .NET 11 app running in Kubernetes. They have `createdump` installed at `/opt/tools/createdump`. Let me look at what's in the current working directory and check if there are any existing Kubernetes manifests or .NET project files to work with.\n\nActually, the user is asking me to:\n1. Configure the .NET app for automatic crash dump collection using environment variables\n2. Provide the Kubernetes pod spec changes needed\n\nFor NativeAOT .NET apps, crash dump collection works differently than regular CoreCLR apps. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n\n- Standard CoreCLR uses environment variables like `COMPlus_DbgEnableMiniDump` and `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` to enable crash dumps, with options for dump type and location\n- But NativeAOT doesn't have the same managed debugging infrastructure, so those variables won't work the same way\n- Starting with .NET 7/8, NativeAOT does support crash dumps through similar environment variables like `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`, `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType`, and `DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName`, though the implementation differs from CoreCLR since the runtime is compiled directly into the application. The key difference is that `createdump` isn't bundled with NativeAOT apps, so you need to explicitly point to it via `DOTNET_CreateDumpPath` or rely on OS-level mechanisms. Let me verify whether NativeAOT in .NET 8+ actually supports these dump environment variables or if there's a different approach required.\n\nFor Kubernetes specifically, I'd need to set up an `emptyDir` volume to capture the dumps, configure the security context with `SYS_PTRACE` capability if using createdump, and pass these environment variables to the container.","outputTokens":1093,"requestId":"9814:37A92F:748BAF0:81434B0:69F40646"},"id":"d815cf36-131e-41a1-b616-705cc46f3f51","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:48:11.845Z","parentId":"596884b0-dcac-477c-b0b7-a58256686026"}
